Starting with 20 cans, Jeff takes 6 (leaving 14), then Tim buys half of his original amount (10), resulting in 24 cans. This interpretation is more natural because if Tim wanted to base his purchase on the remaining amount, the problem would have specified "half of what remained" rather than "half the amount." The wording suggests comparing to the original quantity.
